{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Report updated: cross-references, translation implication for experiential sequences",
    "content": "Report updated. My report already covered both topics in detail (Section 7 on private language/intersubjectivity, and Supplementary Sections S1 and S2 from the previous follow-up). I made the following targeted edits:\n\n1. **Section 7 (Private Language and Intersubjectivity)**: Added cross-reference to S1 at the end of the Assessment, so readers are directed to the full eta-based structural commensurability account.\n\n2. **Section 9 (Translation Challenges)**: Added a new subsection \"Critical Translation Implication: Experiential Sequence is Load-Bearing\" explaining that the ordering and pacing of examples in these essays is not decorative but constitutive of the philosophical argument. Four specific sequences are identified (Sisyphus->cat, 道德仁义礼 reversal, 1+1=2/meme, Ship of Theseus) and translators are warned that paraphrasing, reordering, or abstracting these sequences would destroy the philosophical experiments they embody.\n\n3. **Appendix (Notes on Individual Essays)**: Updated entries for 西西弗斯、班与猫, 后形而上学 整理, 范畴论与境 整理, and K1策略 to explicitly flag each as containing philosophical experiments, with cross-references to S1 and S2, and specific translation guidance.\n\nNo other sections required changes --- the existing S1 and S2 analyses already fully reflected the deeper understanding of intersubjectivity via eta and essays-as-experiments."
  }
}
